The problem with using name@berkeley.edu is that one machine gets stuck
with the load.  That's essentially what we're doing now, except that the 
"name" is hacked to include the real destination.  As various people have
pointed out, breaking the domain up (e.g., name@cs.berkeley.edu) allows
the load to be split up.  As a matter of fact we will probably do such
things in the next 6 months to a year, but even then we'll have to make
each mail domain be an alias (or canonical name) in the host table for
the primary host for the domain.  With close to a thousand hosts at berkeley,
there are problems no matter how we do this.

The consensus of the responses I've received is that many sites use
only domain-style names, and although there are a few complaints,
most non-domain sites can figure out how to reply to mail.  Of course,
it makes a great deal of difference what sites one communicates with.

		Mike

